off their everyday identity was diffused and defeated using the language of the new psychology. By revealing the politics inherent in such language, Hayward raises questions about its deployment in the work of today’s historians.Written in a clear and accessible style, Resisting history provides a fresh and entertaining perspective for anyone interested in questioning the concepts that underlie historical writing and psychological thought today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistory. 0aMysticismxHistory. 0aPsychology and religion. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh  aChristology.  acause and effect.  ademonic possession.  ahauntings.  ainexplicable.  amiraculous events.  amystics.  apsychological theories.  asupernatural.  avisions.1 aHayward, Rhodri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779146740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847791467423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847791467/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles